DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(79)90011-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393279900114
AB  - Empirical evidence, in recent years, suggests that real money balances is mistakenly omitted variable of production. The objective of this paper is to empirically test, within a constant elasticity of substitution production framework, the hypothesis that real balances act as an input-augmenting factor. Regression results for the Indian economy over a two decade period suggest that the bias in technical change caused by the monetization of an erstwhile barter economy was significantly labor-saving in nature. The conventional practice of treating technical change as exogenously determined by time seems, to a large extent, to be unwarranted.
ER  - 

